# Architectural inheritance

Shekyl forked from Monero (which forked from CryptoNote). Code, data
models, threat-model assumptions, and architectural choices were
inherited along with the fork. Most of that inheritance was load-bearing;
some of it is structural drift that contradicts Shekyl's own threat
model and security commitments.

## Scope

This rule applies pre-genesis to all Shekyl code, regardless of
inheritance status. Inherited code is not grandfathered — it is the
primary surface this rule is designed to govern. Post-genesis, this
rule continues to govern new architectural decisions, but inherited
architecture decisions made under it are stable per the standard
amendment process.

## The inherited-architecture rule

Inheriting code is not inheriting architecture. Code is text;
architecture is the property the code delivers against the threat model.
When inherited code's architecture contradicts Shekyl's security
commitments per `00-mission.mdc`, `30-cryptography.mdc`,
`35-secure-memory.mdc`, and `36-secret-locality.mdc`, the architecture
is wrong-for-Shekyl regardless of how well-tested the code is in its
original context.

**Example.** Monero's `transfer_details`-equivalent storage carries
derived per-output secrets directly (combined shared secret, HKDF-derived
scalars, amount-encryption key). The code is well-tested in Monero's
threat model where memory disclosure isn't a primary concern. Shekyl's
threat model (per `30-cryptography.mdc` and `35-secure-memory.mdc`)
makes memory disclosure a primary concern; secrets in orchestrator-persisted
storage contradict this commitment. The Monero code is
correct for Monero; carrying it forward unchanged is wrong for Shekyl.
The disposition is to migrate the data model, not to rationalize the
inheritance.

`36-secret-locality.mdc` says "Rust owns secrets" at the C++/Rust
boundary; this rule extends that principle with the finer-grained
question of *which Rust component* owns secrets. Orchestrator-side
Rust holding derived per-output secrets satisfies `36-secret-locality.mdc`
but contradicts the engine-isolation property the threat model needs.
Both rules apply; this rule catches the residue that
`36-secret-locality.mdc` doesn't.

## When to migrate vs. when to keep

- **Migrate** when inherited architecture contradicts a Shekyl-specific
  security claim. The cost is bounded pre-genesis; the cost is forever
  post-genesis.
- **Keep** when inherited architecture is compatible with Shekyl's
  threat model and migrating would touch many sites without proportional
  benefit.
- **Document** the inheritance and the disposition. "Why is this here?"
  per `05-system-thinking.mdc`'s rule should have a recorded answer for
  every inherited subsystem — either it is load-bearing for Shekyl, or
  it is a deletion target, or it is pending migration.

## The pre-genesis discount

Per `15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`, the pre-V3-launch migration path is
`rm -rf ~/.shekyl` and re-sync. Pre-genesis, schema migrations and
data-model restructurings are bounded work. Post-genesis, they require
migration tooling that runs forever to handle state that exists for a
finite period.

The asymmetry favors doing structural work before genesis. "We'll fix
it in V3.x" loses to "fix it in V3.0" when the work is structural and
the codebase is pre-genesis.

## The "cost-benefit-defer-to-later" anti-pattern

Conventional design discipline weighs immediate cost against immediate
benefit and defers work whose benefit accrues later. For security-load-bearing
structural work, this discipline systematically underweights
the deferred benefit: the cost of fixing structural problems compounds
faster than linearly with each layer of code that depends on the broken
shape, and the value of architectural integrity compounds with each
audit cycle that doesn't have to re-litigate the same finding.

When a discipline review surfaces "this could be fixed structurally
now, or worked around now and fixed structurally later," the default
disposition for security-load-bearing work is **fix structurally now**
unless the cost is genuinely prohibitive (multi-quarter scope; cross-component
coordination that breaks the project's discipline budget).

**Recurrence pattern.** This anti-pattern surfaces in adversarial
design rounds when conventional cost-benefit analysis recommends
incremental work and architectural-integrity analysis recommends
structural work. Round 2's workflow-shape pivot
(per `docs/design/STAGE_1_PR_3_KEY_ENGINE.md` §2.1.1), Round 3's
handle indirection (§3.1.2), and the architectural-inheritance
migration that produced this rule (V3.0 M3a–M3e, per
`docs/design/STAGE_1_PR_3_MIGRATION_PLAN.md`) are three instances
within a single per-trait PR's design rounds.
The pattern's persistence justifies naming it explicitly: when
reviewing a design disposition, ask "is this the cost-benefit-defer-to-later
answer?" If yes, the architectural-integrity-now
answer is the default unless cost is genuinely prohibitive.

## Discovery cadence

Each adversarial pass against design changes compounds the substrate's
discipline budget — the per-trait PR template gains forward-template
content; the project's capacity to surface structural findings
methodically rather than adversarially grows. By PR 4–7, the patterns
surface during pre-flight rather than in late rounds; the rounds
budget compresses without compromising the rigor that produced the
patterns.

The pattern that catches structural findings is "what does this
actually deliver against the threat model?" rather than "is this
internally consistent?" Internal consistency is necessary but not
sufficient; what the design delivers against the threat model is the
load-bearing question.

PR pre-flight checklists should include this question explicitly.
Per-trait extraction PRs should ask, for each trait surface: "what
does this trait deliver against the threat model, and does the
existing data flow support that delivery?" If the answer is "the
trait surface is correct but the data flow contradicts it," the
per-trait PR is not the fix — the fix is an architecture migration
that the per-trait PR documents and triggers.

## Continuous discipline as inheritance prevention

The rule's primary statement governs what to do when inherited
architecture contradicts Shekyl's commitments: migrate. Its corollary,
demonstrated empirically by the PR 3 audit, is that **continuous
application of the discipline produces the same outcome as retroactive
migration at substantially lower total cost.** New code written under
the discipline doesn't need migration; migration applies only where
inherited code wasn't yet under the discipline. As the project's
discipline-application timeline extends, the migration scope shrinks.

The discipline operates with three properties that aren't visible in
single-PR review and become visible only over time:

1. **Distributed application.** No single PR is "the secret-handling
   discipline PR." The discipline applies at every PR's design time
   as part of the priority-hierarchy calculus per `00-mission.mdc`.
   Each individual application is small; the aggregate effect is large.

2. **Asymmetric coverage.** The discipline boundary aligns with the
   "designed-for-Shekyl" / "inherited-from-CryptoNote" boundary. New
   Rust code adopts the discipline; inherited C++ code is left alone
   with deletion targets per `15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`. The result
   is a codebase where post-discipline surfaces are clean and pre-discipline
   surfaces are scheduled for deletion.

3. **Compounding payoff.** Each PR's small discipline application
   doesn't pay back in that PR; it pays back when subsequent PRs'
   design work doesn't have to migrate previously-accumulated drift.
   The PR 3 architectural-inheritance migration is paying back
   accumulated decisions across the Rust components: zero production
   read sites for the field-removal target, zero non-deletion-target
   `SpendInput` construction sites, one production write site (per
   `STAGE_1_PR_3_MIGRATION_AUDIT.md` §5). The audit's smaller-than-anticipated
   scope is the corollary made measurable.

### Operational implication for forward extractions

Pre-flight architectural-inheritance checks transition from
discoveries to confirmations as the discipline's coverage extends.
PR 3's audit was a discovery — the audit's results were unknown
before running it. PR 4 onward's audits are increasingly likely to
be confirmations — the expected outcome is minimal migration; the
audit verifies the expectation. The check's value shifts from
finding migration work to catching the cases where the expectation
breaks.

The pre-flight template should accommodate both shapes: when the
audit confirms minimal migration, PR scope is bounded as anticipated;
when the audit surfaces unexpected migration work, PR scope expands
and design rounds extend. The migration-plan-doc shape
(`docs/design/STAGE_1_PR_3_MIGRATION_PLAN.md` is the first instance)
is reusable as the template for either outcome — the per-PR scope
tables and excluded-sites tables work whether they are short or long.

### The "audits-are-clean-so-compress" anti-pattern

A failure mode adjacent to the cost-benefit-defer-to-later anti-pattern
above: when audits across multiple PRs confirm minimal
migration, the temptation arises to under-invest in the discipline
check itself ("the audits keep coming back clean; we can skip
ahead"). This is exactly wrong. The audits come back clean *because*
the discipline has been continuous; relaxing the check is the
failure mode that produces the next audit's discovery.

The discipline doesn't get to coast on past success. Each PR's rigor
produces the substrate that makes the next PR's rigor easier;
relaxing in any single PR breaks the pattern. The check's continued
strength is itself the property that future audits depend on.

## Density expectations

Architectural-inheritance findings concentrate where Shekyl's threat
model differs most from Monero's. Cryptographic surfaces (`KeyEngine`,
the eventual signing engines) carry the highest concentration; data-flow
surfaces (`LedgerEngine`, `RefreshEngine`) carry less; pure-utility
surfaces (`DaemonEngine`) probably carry none. PR pre-flight
investigations should weight the architectural-inheritance check
proportional to the trait's intersection with Shekyl-specific
threat-model surfaces; trait surfaces with low cryptographic
intersection don't need exhaustive inheritance audits.

The v31 multisig design is an instance of the post-CryptoNote design
discipline being applied correctly during initial design (data types
sync-primitive-free; secrets live in per-signer session state;
message-passing surface carries public material only). Designed-for-Shekyl
architecture passes the inheritance audit by construction;
inherited-from-CryptoNote architecture requires audit and disposition.

## Related rules

- **`00-mission.mdc`** — priority hierarchy. The architectural-inheritance
  rule operates within priority-1 (security) and
  priority-2 (privacy) constraints; inherited architecture that
  contradicts these priorities is rejected per the hierarchy.
- **`05-system-thinking.mdc`** — "why is this here?" rule for
  inherited subsystems. Inherited architecture must have a recorded
  "why" — load-bearing, deletion target, or pending migration.
- **`15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`** — pre-genesis discount and the
  deletion-or-defer discipline. The migration disposition is bounded
  by the pre-genesis posture; this rule extends the deletion-and-debt
  principle to architectural-level migrations.
- **`30-cryptography.mdc`** and **`35-secure-memory.mdc`** — the
  security commitments that inherited architecture is evaluated
  against. Memory-disclosure and zeroization disciplines are the
  threat-model anchors for the secret-flow inheritance findings.
- **`36-secret-locality.mdc`** — "Rust owns secrets" at the C++/Rust
  boundary. This rule extends that principle to which-Rust-component-owns-secrets
  at the orchestrator/engine boundary.
- **`60-no-monero-legacy.mdc`** — removal-not-preservation rule for
  pre-genesis Monero behavior. This rule (architectural-inheritance)
  is the broader principle; `60-no-monero-legacy.mdc` is its specific
  consensus-level application.
